What is Kubernetes (Simple Personal Explanation)

When we build applications using containers (like Docker), we may run many containers on many servers.

For example:

We deploy our application in containers

We run those containers on multiple machines

Sometimes we may have 10, 50, or even 100 containers

Managing them manually becomes very difficult for us.

So we use Kubernetes.

Kubernetes helps us automatically manage our containers across many servers.

What Kubernetes Helps Us Do

When we use Kubernetes, it helps us with many tasks.

1️⃣ Deploying Containers

When we want to run our application, we put it inside a container.

Example:

I build a Docker container for my application

Then I deploy it using Kubernetes

Kubernetes makes sure the container runs properly on a server.

2️⃣ Scaling Applications

Sometimes our application gets more users.

Example:

Initially we run 2 containers

Suddenly traffic increases

So we tell Kubernetes:

"Please run 10 containers instead of 2."

Kubernetes will automatically create more containers for us.

When traffic decreases, we can reduce them again.

3️⃣ Load Balancing

If many users access our application, we don’t want one container to handle everything.

So Kubernetes distributes the traffic for us.

Example:

We have 3 containers:

User Requests
     ↓
Kubernetes Service
 ↓     ↓     ↓
Pod1  Pod2  Pod3

Kubernetes shares traffic between all pods.

4️⃣ Managing Networking and Storage

When our containers need to talk to each other, Kubernetes manages the networking for us.

Example:

One container runs frontend

Another container runs backend

Kubernetes allows these containers to communicate easily.

It also helps us attach storage to containers when needed.

5️⃣ Maintaining Desired State

In Kubernetes, we tell the system what we want.

Example:

I say:

"I want 3 containers running."

If one container crashes, Kubernetes automatically creates a new one for us.

So we don't need to monitor everything manually.

Kubernetes Cluster

When we install Kubernetes, we create something called a cluster.

A cluster contains:

Control Plane (Master)
Worker Nodes

Think of it like:

Manager → Workers
Control Plane (Master Node)

The control plane is like the brain of Kubernetes.

It helps us manage the entire cluster.

It decides:

where our containers should run

how many containers should run

which server should run them

So whenever we give instructions, the control plane manages everything.

API Server

When we interact with Kubernetes, our request goes to the API Server.

Example:

When I run this command:

kubectl get pods

My request goes to the API Server first.

The API server then talks to other Kubernetes components.

So we can say:

The API Server is the main entry point of the cluster.

etcd

etcd is the database of Kubernetes.

It stores all cluster information for us.

Example:

It stores:

which pods are running

which nodes exist

deployment information

services

If we want to know the current state of the cluster, Kubernetes checks etcd.

Controller Manager

The Controller Manager helps us maintain the desired state.

Example:

I say:

"I want 3 pods running."

But currently only 2 pods are running.

The controller manager will create one more pod automatically for us.

So it constantly checks:

Desired State vs Actual State

And fixes problems.

Scheduler

The Scheduler decides where our pods should run.

Example:

We have three worker nodes:

Node1
Node2
Node3

When we create a pod, Kubernetes decides which node should run it.

The scheduler checks:

CPU

Memory

available resources

Then it selects the best node for us.

Worker Nodes

Worker nodes are the machines where our applications actually run.

The control plane manages things, but worker nodes do the real work.

Worker nodes run:

containers

pods

applications

Kubelet

The kubelet is an agent running on each worker node.

Its job is to make sure our containers are running properly.

Example:

If a container crashes, the kubelet will restart it for us.

It constantly talks to the API Server.

Kube Proxy

Kube Proxy manages network communication between pods.

Example:

If one pod wants to talk to another pod, kube-proxy helps route the traffic.

So it helps us connect different parts of our application.

Container Runtime

The container runtime is the software that actually runs containers.

Examples include:

containerd

CRI-O

The runtime helps us:

download container images

start containers

stop containers

Pods

Pods are the smallest unit in Kubernetes.

When we deploy applications in Kubernetes, we don't create containers directly.

Instead, we create pods.

A pod contains one or more containers.

Example:

Pod
 └ Container (nginx)

Pods also share:

network

storage

Namespaces

Namespaces help us organize our cluster.

Example:

If many teams use the same cluster, we can separate resources like this:

dev namespace
test namespace
production namespace

So each team works in its own environment.

Services

Pods are temporary.

If a pod crashes, it gets a new IP address.

This creates problems for us.

So Kubernetes provides Services.

A Service gives:

a stable IP

a DNS name

load balancing

Example:

Service
 ↓
Pod1
Pod2
Pod3

The service automatically sends traffic to available pods.

In One Simple Sentence

When we run many containers on many servers, Kubernetes helps us manage, scale, and keep them running automatically.